nt|Finally, for the first time in almost a week, some people were expecting Team Canada to win a match. Our team (myself and partner ^*BJoey Silver^*N along with ^*BNick Gartaganis^*N-^*BPeter Jones^*N and ^*BKeith Balcombe^*N-^*BGord Campbell^*N) led Poland by 47.5 IMPs at the half way point of the 48-board final of the ^*B2002 IOC Grand Prix^*N.

The match was by no means over, but our team was playing in excellent form. Between the last 24 boards of our semi-final match against Italy and the first 24 boards of the final against Poland, Canada had won 125 IMPs while losing only 22 IMPs!

Nick chose to have Joey and I sit out the 3rd quarter. There were rumblings in the vugraph theatre that this was a mistake. Joey and I were our most experienced pair and we seemed to be hot. Nick, however, had noticed that the other 2 pairs had been hot as well. Nick knew he wanted to play Joey and me in the 4th quarter and he wanted to make sure we were well rested in case the match became close.

How did I feel about this? Well, I would have preferred to have played, but Nick's reasoning did seem logical. It actually didn't matter if I had agreed with Nick's reasoning or not - he was the Captain and his decisions up until then had been double dummy. Nick had the confidence and respect of the other 5 members of our team and none of us would have questioned his decision.

It turned out that Poland outscored Canada 39 IMPs to 9 IMPs in the 12-board 3rd quarter. There was a lot of people in the vugraph theatre saying, "I told you so", but the 30 IMPs we lost had very little to do with who had been playing for Canada. Poland had taken a few aggressive positions, found some fortuitous layouts, and won a few swings. None of that mattered now anyway. What mattered was that there were 12 boards left and Canada still led by 17.5 IMPs.
|
pg| ***** 1 ***** |


nt|
In the fourth quarter Joey and I were back on vugraph where we would faced ^*BMichal Kwiecien^*N-^*BJacek Pszczola^*N, the reigning World Open Pairs champions. Keith and Gord sat down to play against ^*BCesary Balicki^*N-^*BAdam Zmudzinski^*N in the closed room.

This is about as good as it gets in tournament bridge - playing the last segment of a close match against a great pair in the final of a major tournament. I had been here before, but a number of factors made this opportunity especially exciting: we were serious underdogs, the press was everywhere, we were on vugraph, and it was my birthday! While we were waiting to receive the first board to play, I reflected on similar moments in my bridge career.

In the World Junior Teams Championships in 1991, I was part of the Canadian Team that had unexpectedly reached the finals. My partner, ^*BGeoff Hampson^*N, and I had played the last segment of a very close match on vugraph. We played well, but our team lost the match. At the time I don't think I appreciated the gravity of the situation. I recalled that my thoughts had been along the lines of "what a great experience this will be regardless of the outcome of the match". Loser!

In the Bermuda Bowl in 1995, I was part of the Canadian Team that had unexpectedly reached the finals. My partner, ^*BGeorge Mittelman^*N, and I sat on the bench during the last segment of a close match. Our Captain, ^*BIrving Litvack^*N, had wanted to play George and me, but I was terrified and told Irving that I was too tired to play (an excuse). The rest of our team played just fine, but our American opponents (especially ^*BJeff Meckstroth^*N and ^*BEric Rodwell^*N) played better and Canada lost the match. I am sure that our team would have lost even if I had been playing, but I hated myself for a couple of years after that for being too afraid to play down the stretch. I swore to myself that it would not happen again.
|
pg| ***** 2 ***** |


nt|
My current regular partner, ^*BBrad Moss^*N, and I had been in this type of position several times during this past few years. We lost in the finals of both the 2000 World Transnational Teams and the 2001 Spingold. In both of these events our team had not been expected to get that far and in both cases our team lost at the end.

The good news was that I had managed to get over my fear of playing in pressure situations and played the last segments of both of these events. I could have won the Transnational Teams (against a very strong team that included Adam and Cesary) on the third last board if I had bid a slam. There was no way that our team could have won the Spingold regardless of what I did. Our opponents (^*BRose Meltzer^*N's reigning Bermuda Bowl champions) just played too well that day.

Brad and I have also had a series of near misses in major pairs events, notably the 1999 Life Master Pairs (we finished 2nd) and several Cavendish Invitational Pairs (where we always seem to come close, but so far there have been no cigars). Brad and I finally won a big event in 2001 when we were part of the team that won the Reisinger. I felt absolutely no pressure when we played the last session of that event, but I suspect that was due to the fact that I had no idea that our team was in contention for the win.

When the first board of the last quarter of the 2002 IOC Grand Prix was placed on the table, I felt that I was ready. I felt the pressure, but I was not nervous. I was ready to play. I knew that my partner would be ready too. Joey is a born competitor and he had also been here many times before. Keith and Gord were new at this, but as far as I could tell, none of my "inexperienced" teammates had let the pressure get to them yet. I expected them to do fine, but there was no point in thinking about it - whatever happened at the other table was out of my control.

