What happened next was that a whole bunch of Canadians became very excited! It was not just members of our team. Most of their wives, the members of the Canadian Women's Team, Canadian Bridge Federation President ^*BRay Lee^*N (who had been instrumental in putting our team together), and various other Canadian supporters (including my friends ^*BGeorge Mittelman^*N and ^*BEric Kokish^*N) also got into the act. Canada had never won a Gold Medal in a team event of this stature before. This was a great moment for Canadian bridge!

My only previous win in a major event had come a few months earlier in the Reisinger. This win felt much better. For one thing, it was not completely surprising that the team I had played on in the Reisinger had won the event. What happened in Salt Lake City was completely surprising.  In addition, a controversial appeal decided the Reisinger and left some very bad feelings in the air. There was nothing except good feelings in the air right then in Salt Lake City!

Our Captain and leader, Nick Gartaganis, had done a magnificent job steering the ship. His task was made easier because all of our members had played their best bridge, all of us had behaved like gentlemen, and there had been no acrimony between partners or teammates. Still, being Captain is never easy or fun and Nick had a lot of difficult decisions to make. The fact that he was able to both make effective decisions while playing as well as he did speaks volumes for Nick's bridge ability and character. Thanks to Nick, Peter, Keith, and Gord for helping to make the 2002 IOC Grand Prix one for the highlight reels!

And a special thanks to Joey Silver, my dear partner and dear friend. Joey was the one who really taught me to play this game. This win would not have meant quite as much if I had been playing with anyone else.|
