Here are 2 important things that I learned from this experience. I had suspected that these things were true, but it was nice to get confirmation:

1. There are a lot of bridge players out there who, on any given deal, are capable of playing as well as any world class player. What separates the world class players from the masses is consistency. All of the players on my team were experts, but before the IOC Grand Prix, most of us would not be considered "world class". However, those players rose to the occasion. They played as well as they possibly could. It turned out that this was good enough to beat Italy and Poland. 

This win should be an inspiration to all aspiring bridge champions: it is possible to beat the best. All you have to do is not make very many mistakes and hope that you make more good decisions than the opponents. This is ^*Bmuch^*N easy said than done, of course, but you should take some comfort in knowing that it is possible!
|
pg| ***** 185 ***** |


nt|

2. That it is possible to win playing a natural system with very few agreements. Joey and I played ^*Bvery^*N few conventions and we had spent no more than half an hour discussing our system. As far as I can remember we did not have a single bidding misunderstanding. We had a lot of big hands to bid and I felt that overall we had done well.

In theory the IOC Grand Prix was a tournament where only simple systems were allowed, but in practice this meant that some of the partnerships could not play their preferred 2-level opening bids. The Poles still played their Polish 1@Cs. Their was an Australian pair playing the Symetric Relay. There were several Precision pairs, including Berkowitz and Cohen from the United States, playing a very sophisticated version. 

System is not what bridge is all about. Joey introduced me to this radical idea almost 10 years ago and now I know it is true. Winning is about making fewer errors and better guesses than the opponents. For me playing a natural system is very liberating and this allows me to focus on the other (more important) aspects of the game. Try it some time. It is a fun way to play and it works!|